<Layout title="Simulanious Equations">
    A Simulanious equation is a set of equations (2 or more) with 2 or more variables
    <h2>Example</h2>
    \(3x + 2y = 30\) <br>
    \(3x + 5y = 42\) <br>
    <br>
    to solve it you do
    <br>
    \(  3x + 2y = 30\) <br>
    \(- 3x + 5y = 42\) <br>
    It's a minus because both signs are equal (the + and the +) <br>
    which gives you <br>
    \(  -3y = -12\) <br>
    which is simplified down to <br>
    \(y = 4\) <br>
    now substitute y into one of the above equations <br>
    \(3x + 2y = 30\) <br>
    \(3x + 8 = 30\) <br>
    \(3x = 22\) <br>
    \(x = 7.\periodfl{3}\) <br>
    now check it works in the other equation <br>
    \(3x + 5y = 42\) <br>
    \(22 + 20 = 42\) <br>
    <br>
    
    

</Layout>


